<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title/><link>https://notes.bencuan.me/cs61b/algorithms/searching/</link><description>Recent content on</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en</language><atom:link href="https://notes.bencuan.me/cs61b/algorithms/searching/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title/><link>https://notes.bencuan.me/cs61b/algorithms/searching/binary-search/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://notes.bencuan.me/cs61b/algorithms/searching/binary-search/</guid><description>&lt;h1 id="binary-search"&gt;
 Binary Search
 &lt;a class="anchor" href="#binary-search"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Binary search is a way of finding a specific node in a tree. It only works on 





&lt;a href="https://notes.bencuan.me/cs61b/abstract-data-types/binary-trees/" rel="noopener"
 class="internal-link" data-src="https://notes.bencuan.me/cs61b/abstract-data-types/binary-trees/"&gt;binary trees&lt;/a&gt; due to its helpful sorted property. It simply traverses the tree, moving left if the current node is too large or right if it is too small.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Binary search runs in $\Theta(\log(n))$ time for bushy trees, which is also the number of layers in a tree.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id="the-algorithm"&gt;
 The Algorithm
 &lt;a class="anchor" href="#the-algorithm"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;div class="highlight"&gt;&lt;pre tabindex="0" style="color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;-webkit-text-size-adjust:none;"&gt;&lt;code class="language-java" data-lang="java"&gt;&lt;span style="display:flex;"&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style="color:#66d9ef"&gt;public&lt;/span&gt; BST &lt;span style="color:#a6e22e"&gt;find&lt;/span&gt;(BST T, Key sk) {
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="display:flex;"&gt;&lt;span&gt; &lt;span style="color:#66d9ef"&gt;if&lt;/span&gt; (T &lt;span style="color:#f92672"&gt;==&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style="color:#66d9ef"&gt;null&lt;/span&gt;) {
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="display:flex;"&gt;&lt;span&gt; &lt;span style="color:#66d9ef"&gt;return&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style="color:#66d9ef"&gt;null&lt;/span&gt;;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="display:flex;"&gt;&lt;span&gt; }
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="display:flex;"&gt;&lt;span&gt; &lt;span style="color:#66d9ef"&gt;if&lt;/span&gt; (sk.&lt;span style="color:#a6e22e"&gt;equals&lt;/span&gt;(T.&lt;span style="color:#a6e22e"&gt;key&lt;/span&gt;)) {
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="display:flex;"&gt;&lt;span&gt; &lt;span style="color:#66d9ef"&gt;return&lt;/span&gt; T;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="display:flex;"&gt;&lt;span&gt; } &lt;span style="color:#66d9ef"&gt;else&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style="color:#66d9ef"&gt;if&lt;/span&gt; (sk &lt;span style="color:#f92672"&gt;&amp;lt;&lt;/span&gt; T.&lt;span style="color:#a6e22e"&gt;key&lt;/span&gt;) {
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="display:flex;"&gt;&lt;span&gt; &lt;span style="color:#66d9ef"&gt;return&lt;/span&gt; find(T.&lt;span style="color:#a6e22e"&gt;left&lt;/span&gt;, sk);
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="display:flex;"&gt;&lt;span&gt; } &lt;span style="color:#66d9ef"&gt;else&lt;/span&gt; {
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="display:flex;"&gt;&lt;span&gt; &lt;span style="color:#66d9ef"&gt;return&lt;/span&gt; find(T.&lt;span style="color:#a6e22e"&gt;right&lt;/span&gt;, sk);
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="display:flex;"&gt;&lt;span&gt; }
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="display:flex;"&gt;&lt;span&gt;}
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description></item><item><title>Breadth First Search (DFS)</title><link>https://notes.bencuan.me/cs61b/algorithms/searching/breadth-first-search-bfs/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://notes.bencuan.me/cs61b/algorithms/searching/breadth-first-search-bfs/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;Breadth First Search (BFS), like 





&lt;a href="https://notes.bencuan.me/cs61b/algorithms/searching/depth-first-search-dfs/" rel="noopener"
 class="internal-link" data-src="https://notes.bencuan.me/cs61b/algorithms/searching/depth-first-search-dfs/"&gt;Depth First Search (DFS)&lt;/a&gt;, is a method of &lt;strong&gt;traversing a graph.&lt;/strong&gt; BFS simply traverses in a different order, but otherwise is very similar to DFS.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The main difference is that BFS &lt;strong&gt;visits all children before any subgraphs.&lt;/strong&gt; In a tree, we call this &lt;strong&gt;level order.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;


&lt;img src="https://notes.bencuan.me/cs61b/algorithms/searching/../../img/assets/image%20%28110%29.png" width="auto" alt="" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For the example tree above, a level order traversal would go in this order: &lt;strong&gt;D B F A C E G.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Depth First Search (DFS)</title><link>https://notes.bencuan.me/cs61b/algorithms/searching/depth-first-search-dfs/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://notes.bencuan.me/cs61b/algorithms/searching/depth-first-search-dfs/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="depth-first-traversal"&gt;
 Depth First Traversal
 &lt;a class="anchor" href="#depth-first-traversal"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Before we move on to searching, let&amp;rsquo;s talk about &lt;strong&gt;traversing. Traversal&lt;/strong&gt; is the act of &lt;strong&gt;visiting nodes in a specific order.&lt;/strong&gt; This can be done either in trees or in graphs.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For trees in particular, there are &lt;strong&gt;three main ways&lt;/strong&gt; to traverse.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;


&lt;img src="https://notes.bencuan.me/cs61b/algorithms/searching/../../img/assets/image%20%2889%29.png" width="auto" alt="The example tree we will use for traversal illustrations." /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The first way is &lt;strong&gt;inorder&lt;/strong&gt; traversal, which visits &lt;strong&gt;all left children&lt;/strong&gt;, then &lt;strong&gt;the node itself,&lt;/strong&gt; then &lt;strong&gt;all right children.&lt;/strong&gt; The end result should be that the nodes were visited in &lt;strong&gt;sorted order.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>